The J Parker is a rooftop bar that happens to serve food. It's a great place to bring friends and hangout.  The J Parker (named after Lincoln's often-drunk bodyguard) is a rooftop bar located on top of the Lincoln Hotel in Lincoln Park. Avoiding the downtown tourist crowds, there is barely a line to get in here.  The best views are the open-roofed south-facing view. But even if you don't get seating there, the other views are solid as well. Protip: Check out the cool window view in the restroom, you won't be disappointed.  Staff here is great, kind, and friendly. Expect chatty bartenders who will give you some solid recommendations. The liquor selection is above standard with a few interesting choices. Expect ~$15 per cocktail. For a good rooftop bar, is that so bad?  Haven't tried the food yet here and I doubt I ever will. This bar hits all the spots I want and then some.  5/5. Easy to get to, great views, not-too-pricey drinks, and solid place to bring your out-of-town friends. Def one I'll keep coming back to.

I was finally able to visit this rooftop bar in my neighborhood after over a year of wondering what it was like up there. It honestly took me so long to stop by because I was worried there'd always be a long wait or that it'd be too crowded, because, you know, it's a rooftop bar with incredible views. Luckily, when my boyfriend and I stopped in this past week on a sunny, 60-degree evening, there were a few open seats with a fabulous view of the skyline and Lincoln Park Zoo. Score!  After we selected a prime cushioned bench along the glass paneling facing the lake, a cheerful waitress appeared within a few minutes with menus and a carafe of water. We were able to take a few minutes to peruse our options, and while a few of the restaurant's signature drinks caught my eye, I started with a glass of Cab Sauv. I also ordered a helping of truffle fries for the two of us to enjoy while we drank.  While I wish my wine pour was a little more generous, I know it's not always typical to offer generous pours, and the wine tasted like it was quality. Plus, who could be ~actually~ disappointed with much with a view like the one up there at the J Parker?! The truffle fries were also perfectly warm and crispy, and stayed warm for a good amount of time even though we were sitting outside where it began to get pretty chilly and windy.  After about an hour, we moved inside, because a few tables had opened up. By this time (around 8:30pm) the outside was dark, so the whole skyline was lit up, and we could see all of the city's pretty lights through the all-glass windows surrounding us. While sitting inside, I ordered a drink that I'll never forget, called the Isla de las Muñecas, which featured mezcal, pineapple rum, horchata (!!!), jalapeño, poblano, lime, firewater bitters, and cinnamon dusting. Um... it was the BEST. I'm not a big fan of spice, but I almost now want to solely drink spicy cocktails for the rest of my life after having this one. Dare I say it's better than one that's sweet? Maybe.  From the quick service despite the large number of people inside to the overall cool aspect of being able to drink while taking a look at the city from a different perspective, definitely give The J Parker a try!

Each of cocktails we ordered were $13 but were well worth the price. I especially loved the Bernie Lomax, a citrus-forward drink that blended well with the gin. The Josie's on Vacation was a delicious and spicy mezcal cocktail. Their frozen drinks were also incredibly refreshing, though admittedly very sweet.
